fr:frontmatter.fr:title: \infty -categories: a first course

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: These are lecture notes for a course delivered through the Taught Courses Center (Bath, Bristol, Imperial, Oxford, Warwick) in Fall 2023. The goal is to introduce the language of ‚àû-categories (as quasi-categories), hopefully enabling the audience to tackle more ad- vanced texts and read some of the literature employing this language. Many proofs are omitted, some of which are difficult and would require developing substantial extra ma- terial. On the other hand, this omission allows us to talk about a number of subjects, including constructing ‚àû-categories, (co)limits and presentability. We end with spectra and the ùêæ-theory of stable ‚àû-categories.

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: A quasicategory, \infty -category, or weak Kan complex is a simplicial set in which every inner horn has a (not necessarily unique) filler; in particular, every composable pair has a composite.
The category of quasicategories is the full subcategory of sSet spanned by quasicategories.

fr:title.text: Equivalence of morphisms is an equivalence relation

fr:frontmatter.fr:title: Equivalence of morphisms is an equivalence relation

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: Equivalence of morphisms in a quasicategory is an equivalence relation.

fr:title.text: Composites in a quasicategory are unique up to equivalence

fr:frontmatter.fr:title: Composites in a quasicategory are unique up to equivalence

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: Let x\xrightarrow {f} y, y\xrightarrow {g} z, and x\xrightarrow {h,h'} z be morphisms in a quasicategory so that h\overset {\sigma }{\simeq }g\circ f and h'\overset {\sigma '}{\simeq } g\circ f. Then there is an equivalence h\simeq h'.
Note that the proof of the previous proposition looks very much like a traditional, 1-categorical diagram chase.

fr:title.text: The nerve functor is fully faithful

fr:frontmatter.fr:title: The nerve functor is fully faithful

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: The nerve functor is fully faithful, and its essential image consists of quasicategories such that each inner horn admits a unique filler.

fr:title.text: Homotopy category of an infinity category

fr:frontmatter.fr:title: Homotopy category of an infinity category

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: By abstract nonsense, the nerve functor has a left adjoint, called one-truncation or the homotopy category, and written \tau _1 or h. In particular, it sends a quasicategory C to the category whose objects come from the quasicategory and whose morphisms are equivalence classes of morphisms in the quasicategory.

fr:title.text: The counit of the nerve adjunction is an isomorphism

fr:frontmatter.fr:title: The counit of the nerve adjunction is an isomorphism

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: Because the nerve functor is fully faithful, the counit of the adjunction between the nerve and homotopy category is an isomorphism h(N(C))\cong C.
A morphism x\xrightarrow {f} y in a quasicategory is an isomorphism if there exists an inverse morphism y\xrightarrow {g} x together with equivalences g\circ f\simeq 1_x, f\circ g\simeq 1_y.
A Kan complex is a simplicial set in which every horn has a filler; equivalently, an \infty -groupoid is a quasicategory in which every morphism is an isomorphism.
The singular simplicial complex of a space X is a Kan complex.
A Kan complex is a simplicial set in which every horn has a filler; equivalently, an \infty -groupoid is a quasicategory in which every morphism is an isomorphism.

The singular simplicial complex functor from spaces to simplicial sets is the right adjoint to the geometric realization functor. By abstract nonsense, this is given by \operatorname {Sing}(X)_n = \operatorname {Top}(|\Delta ^n|, X).

fr:title.text: Geometric realization of a simplicial set

fr:frontmatter.fr:title: Geometric realization of a simplicial set

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: Let \Delta \to Top send n to the topological n-simplex \{x_0,x_1,\dots ,x_n\in \mathbb {R}: x_0+\dots +x_1 = 0, x_i\geq 0\}. Then the geometric realization of a simplicial set is the Kan extension of this functor to sSet.

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: In the forwards direction, suppose that the isomorphisms are natural, and further that the left-hand square commutes; the case in which the right-hand square commutes is similar. By the naturality of the isomorphism in C, the transpose of kf^\sharp is (Gk) f^\flat , while by naturality in D, the transpose of (Fh)g^\sharp is hg^\flat . Since the maps are equal, their transposes must also be equal; this is commutativity of the square on the right.
A morphism y\xrightarrow {r}x is a retraction, post-inverse, or split epimorphism if there exists a morphism x\xrightarrow {s}y such that rs = 1_x.
A morphism x\xrightarrow {s}y is a section, pre-inverse, or split monomorphism if there exists a morphism y\xrightarrow {r}x such that rs = 1_x.
